## Important Directories

### `/app` - Next.js App Router

The main application directory using Next.js 16 App Router pattern.

**Route Groups:**
- **`(protected)`**: Routes that require authentication
- **`(public)`**: Public routes accessible without authentication

**Key Files:**
- **`app/layout.tsx`**: Root layout that wraps all pages
- **`app/page.tsx`**: Home page route (`/`)
- **`app/globals.css`**: Global styles and Tailwind CSS directives
- **`app/favicon.ico`**: Site favicon

**Route Structure:**
- **`app/(protected)/dashboard/`**: Main dashboard routes
- **`app/(protected)/dashboard/posts/`**: Posts management routes
- **`app/(public)/login/`**: Login page

**Conventions:**
- Use file-based routing (folders = routes)
- `page.tsx` files define routes
- `layout.tsx` files define shared layouts
- `loading.tsx` files define loading states
- `error.tsx` files define error boundaries
- `not-found.tsx` files define 404 pages
- Route groups `(name)` don't affect URL structure
- Parallel routes `@slot` enable simultaneous rendering
- Intercepting routes `(.)` catch navigation for modals

### `/actions` - Server Actions

Next.js 16 Server Actions for server-side mutations and data operations.

**Structure:**
- Feature-based organization (auth, posts, comments, users)
- Each file exports Server Action functions
- Uses reusable HTTP functions from `lib/api/axios.ts`

**Conventions:**
- One file per feature/resource
- Functions return `{ data }` or `{ error }` objects
- Use `"use server"` directive (implicit in this directory)
- Handle errors consistently using `lib/api/errors.ts`

### `/components` - UI Components

Reusable UI components organized by purpose.

**Subdirectories:**
- **`components/ui/`**: shadcn/ui components and custom UI primitives
- **`components/partials/`**: Layout partials (sidebar, header, navigation)

**Conventions:**
- UI components are framework-agnostic when possible
- Partials are layout-specific and may use Next.js features
- Follow shadcn/ui patterns for consistency
- Use TypeScript for type safety

### `/features` - Feature Modules

Feature-based organization following domain-driven design principles.

**Structure:**
- Each feature has its own directory
- Features contain: `types.ts`, `queries.ts`, `mutations.ts`, `schema.ts`, `ui/`
- UI components are in `feature/ui/` subdirectory
- Barrel exports (`index.ts`) for clean imports

**Current Features:**
- **`auth`**: Authentication (store, types, login form)
- **`posts`**: Posts management (queries, mutations, forms, lists)

**Conventions:**
- Feature folders are self-contained
- Types are feature-specific (not in `/types`)
- UI components are co-located with feature logic
- Use barrel exports for public API

### `/lib` - Shared Utilities

Contains reusable utility functions and shared code organized by domain.

**Subdirectories:**
- **`lib/api/`**: API client, endpoints, error handling
- **`lib/auth/`**: Authentication utilities (cookies, tokens)
- **`lib/query/`**: TanStack Query configuration and utilities
- **`lib/env.ts`**: Type-safe environment variable access
- **`lib/routes.ts`**: Centralized route constants
- **`lib/utils.ts`**: Common utilities (e.g., `cn()`)

**Conventions:**
- Export pure functions when possible
- Keep utilities framework-agnostic when possible
- Use TypeScript for type safety
- Organize by domain/concern

### `/types` - Shared Types

TypeScript type definitions shared across features.

**Conventions:**
- Only general/shared types (e.g., `ApiError`)
- Feature-specific types live in `features/{feature}/types.ts`
- Use `export type` for type-only exports

### `/hooks` - Custom React Hooks

Reusable React hooks for common functionality.

**Conventions:**
- Use `use` prefix for hook names
- Export hooks individually
- Keep hooks focused and reusable

### `/.cursor/rules` - Cursor Rules

Project-specific rules and guidelines for AI assistance.

**Existing Rules:**
- `cursor-rules.mdc`: How to add/edit cursor rules
- `error-checking.mdc`: Error checking workflow
- `self-improvement.mdc`: Self-improvement guidelines
- `project-structure.mdc`: This file

**Conventions:**
- Use kebab-case for filenames
- Always use `.mdc` extension
- Place all rules in this directory

